post_text:
ALL JAMESTOWN PUBLIC SCHOOL STUDENTS TO RECEIVE FREE BREAKFAST AND LUNCH
All Jamestown Public Schools students will receive free meals for the start of the 2020/2021 school year via a United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) waiver as the country continues to recover from the COVID-19 pandemic. These meals will be made available as late as December 31, 2020 or until the available federal funding is exhausted.

The available meals include breakfast and lunch for all students, either virtual or in-person, and includes “to-go” pickups. Extra milks, ala carte items, and super-size entrees will still be charged to the individual account.

Current funds in a student account can be held for when charges to meals resumes. Families are still requested to complete Free and Reduced Meal Program applications as the free meals are temporary and dependent upon available federal funds. In addition, there are also other household and school district benefits to qualifying for the Free and Reduced Meal Program.

shared_text:
Jamestown High School
August 31 at 8:07 AM ·

*** Activities Update
Due to capacity restrictions, ticketed JHS fall activities (football, soccer, swimming, volleyball) will have limited attendance available. Each rostered student-athlete will be given four vouchers for each home contest (2 for away) that they may share with family & friends. The voucher is not your pass to get in but rather an opportunity to purchase an admission ticket. Non-ticketed events such as cross country, golf and tennis we are asking no more than two spectators per student competing.
Masks will be expected at all JHS Indoor facilities as well as encouraged at outdoor facilities. Social/Physical distancing rules also apply and need to be respected. Failure to do so may limit future opportunity to attend events.

post_text:
Families:

We are looking forward to August 27 when we have a chance to see our students again. With that said, we recognize that there is an understandable anxiety mixed with excitement to return to school. The source of much of the anxiety is the unknown. I am sharing an excellent resource from the North Dakota School Nurse Association that targets schools specifically. It is a 40 minute video that likely answers many questions that you may have related to best practices, quarantine, expectations, and "what happens if...".

Please take some time to watch this excellent video from the ND School Nurse Association.

Rob Lech

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I6x4r0ZaVEA&feature=youtu.be

For your convenience, CVHD is hosting a drive-up vaccination clinic on August 5 from 9am-3pm at the Jamestown Civic Center to serve area students to safely receive their vaccine.

*Appointments are required

*Paperwork must be completed before arrival

*Parents do not need to be with student, however, a signature is required on a consent form in advance.

Target of this event are:

*Students entering the 11th grade in need of the MCV4 vaccine (must be 16 years old) and;

*Students entering the 7th grade in need of the Tdap vaccine

To schedule an appointment or for more information, call Central Valley Health at 252-8130.”

Kim Lee, RN | Director of Nursing
Central Valley Health District

There are lots of changes taking place in front of Jamestown Middle School because of the Safe Routes to School grant for safety upgrades at JMS. The upgrades will provide the safest possible thoroughfare for school, but with the additional plans
to improve sightlines for drivers and create a more efficient and safer dropoff and pickup plan. This includes some bumpouts on second, a mid-street crosswalk refuge, a dropoff lane on the southside of the building, moving the bike rack, and additional sidewalks.

post_text:
The district will soon be posting a link to a Long Range Plan and an accompanying survey to gather information from stakeholders on the key areas of: 1) academic and extracurricular programs, 2) instructional and administrative staffing, 3) facility needs and utilization, and 4) district tax levies.

A survey will be included to allow for sharing perspective on this report. The survey will close on Tuesday, June 9. It is open to school personnel, students, parents, and community members of the Jamestown School District.

Please check www.jamestown.k12.nd.us to find a link to the report and survey. It will be uploaded no later than Wednesday, June 3.

post_text:
Jamestown Public Schools is pleased to announce that Jamestown High School will be holding a graduation ceremony on May 24, 2020. This was made possible based upon guidance from Governor Doug Burgum and the recent receipt of the ND Smart Restart High School Graduation Ceremony Guidance from the North Dakota Department of Public Instruction.

While accommodations will include limits on guests, the event will be live cast to ensure that all people interested in supporting the Class of 2020 in this capstone achievement will be able to do so.

Specific guidelines will be sent out directly to graduates and families and will be posted on the school district’s website after consultation with Central Valley Health, emergency services, and city officials.
text:
Jamestown Public Schools is pleased to announce that Jamestown High School will be holding a graduation ceremony on May 24, 2020. This was made possible based upon guidance from Governor Doug Burgum and the recent receipt of the ND Smart Restart High School Graduation Ceremony Guidance from the North Dakota Department of Public Instruction.

While accommodations will include limits on guests, the event will be live cast to ensure that all people interested in supporting the Class of 2020 in this capstone achievement will be able to do so.

Specific guidelines will be sent out directly to graduates and families and will be posted on the school district’s website after consultation with Central Valley Health, emergency services, and city officials.

Thank you to all of our support staff. This includes our paras, custodian staff, food service, maintenance, business office, secretaries, and all other positions. We recognize that you are all the glue that makes education possible. During this pandemic, you have been asked to re-imagine your positions, take on new responsibilities, and take on new challenges. You have modeled for our students how to take on change and persevere. Our community and the school recognize the amazing work that you do for our students.

Robert Lech, Superintendent

Upon the recommendation of the National Federation of High School Sports, NDHSAA Board of Directors has approved that sports physicals from this past school year (2019-20) will be accepted as well for the upcoming school year (2020-21) provided that the parent & student complete and submit a waiver form (Formerly Form B).

Once the form is released it will be available at the JHS and JMS offices and a link will be posted on the website.

Jamestown Middle School
April 23 at 9:35 AM ·

The 24th Annual Jamestown Middle School Penny Drive will be held April 27 - May 3rd. Since 1997, JMS students and staff have raised $165,707 for those in need. We take pride in giving to our community and feel it is a large part of who we are at JMS. Each year students look forward to competing to help those in need. This year, due to COVID-19, we feel that we need to give in an untraditional way to those in our community. Please check out the JMS Penny Drive Choice Board to see how you can participate. We hope that you will join us in any way that you can! #jmspennydrive2020 #bepositivedopositivejms

post_text: The Jamestown School District is fortunate to have the outstanding support of many in the community of Jamestown as we transition to an online environment. With connectivity as a key piece of virtual learning, our students have benefited from online providers (Daktel and CSI), but also from donations. The Jamestown School District was able to provide wi-fi hot spots to allow students to access our on-line learning programs through charitable donations from local businesses. We extend our thanks to Fred's Den, The Wonder Bar, and the Knights of Columbus for their generosity in providing this funding!

If your family needs assistance from JPS to line up internet connectivity please notify us by NOON FRIDAY MARCH 27th (tomorrow).

We will need time to coordinate with Internet Service Providers. We want to be up and running as soon as possible for our students.

Many have already been contacted by our local providers.

Tech Support hours will be 8 AM until 4 PM daily starting Monday March 30, 2020.

If your family needs an additional Chromebook or support on district Chromebooks please use the Chromebook hotline, 952-3208.

We will be using the Main entrance to the Middle School as a drop off and pick up point. Please call and schedule a time and we will meet you there.

Thank you for patience and support as we go forward.

Mike Armitage
Technology Director
Jamestown Public Schools

post_text:
If your Chromebook needs repair please call 952-3208. If it is not answered please stay on the line as your call will be forwarded to a cell phone. We will be open from 8-4:30 for repair needs.

We will meet you at the Middle School front lobby and exchange your Chromebook for another. Please bring the a/c adapter as well, we have many models and you’re a/c adapter may not work with your replacement unit.

Home cleaning for the Chromebook. Please use one of the available wipes (Lysol, Clorox, genic or a water - alcohol solution (1 part 70% alcohol 3 parts water) wring the wipe/rag out so it is not dripping wet and wipe the keyboard. None of the Chromebooks are touch screen so please wipe with a damp cloth and warm water to clean. The wipes will damage the screen so please do not use the wipes on it.
